Since we arrived early, we decided to grab a drink at the bar at District Kitchen. We ordered a Red Sangria, Strawberry Mojito, and Paloma but the bartender messed up the order and gave us two Strawberry Mojitos and a Paloma. We didn't accept the wrong drink and demanded the fix. The Red Sangria consisted of red wine, rum, and, prosecco. It said it came with fresh fruit but it didn't. It didn't even come stirred or with a stirrer. The Strawberry Mojito consisted of white rum, mint, muddled strawberries, lime juice, and prosecco shaken and served over the rocks. It was sweet and fruity. The Paloma consisted of tequila, grapefruit juice, lime, simple syrup, and soda.  We told the hostess that we had a reservation and wanted a table in the patio. It was nice that we didn't have to close our tabs but rather transfer them. The hostess brought us to a table in the patio. We waited about 15 minutes in the patio for a server to take our order but no one ever came so I went up to the hostess stand to tell them we were ready to order.  We were glad we ordered appetizers including a cheese platter and Mac and Cheese because despite the almost empty dining room, it took about 45 minutes for our entrees to come out. Our cheese platter consisted of Greenhill, Mahon, and Idiazabal. Greenhill reminded me of a brie cheese due to its sweetness, creaminess, and smooth texture. Mahon reminded me of a muenster cheese due to its richness,  creaminess, and nuttiness. Idiazabal was smoky and nutty. All of these cheeses were served with honey and assorted toasted pita chips, some plain and some with sesame seeds. The Mac and Cheese consisted of fusilli pasta, three cheese bechamel, herbed bread crumbs, and shaved Grana Padano cheese. It was served in a cast iron skill. The flavors were much lighter than expected.  For dinner, the guys ordered Creekstone 8oz Burgers with Cheese and Bacon but with varying temperatures - rare and medium rare and varying condiments. The Creekstone Burger consisted of 8oz beef patty, lettuce tomato, pickles, cheese, and crispy bacon in between brioche buns. It was served with fries and ketchup.  We didn't think anyone could mess up a burger. My friend's burger was medium rare instead of rare, had white cheddar cheese, and had no pickles instead of pickles while my boyfriend's burger was rare instead of medium rare, had american cheese, and with pickles instead of no pickles. We were extremely hungry and didn't want to wait any longer for a remake of the burgers. I ordered a half portion of the Grilled Salmon, which was served over butter beans and kale ragout, leeks, fennel, and a crispy artichoke in a sambucca and dill broth. Since I asked for no black pepper, the dish was a little too salty.

Ahi poke...Fresh!!! Salmon... Fresh! Great Lakes on tap
They did not honor the drink special advertised, several customers were upset. They didn't even remove it from the chaulkboard

Came here last night with my husband and it was incredibly cute and charming. Outdoor seating was lovely. Tables were set far apart so not to hear other conversations. Motorcade came zipping by causing a bit of mayhem while being seated. Perks of living in DC I guess. Food was delicious. I got the jumbo lump crab with avocado toast and the burrata salad. In the salad there was too much basil but very fresh burrata and gorgeous heirloom tomatoes. Our waiter was a good sport when we kept ordering more water. We could have just used the hose. Kidding. Date night while in the city was nice.
A variety of tasty dishes. Mac and cheese, Brussels sprout, desserts. The list goes on. Do be aware large groups should bring cash as the number of card payments is limited.
Went there twice during a recent trip. Had dinner and brunch, both were great
It's pretty good.  Wide selection but not much adventure.  Solid beers and drinks.

Good spot for classic american fare and cocktails. Service is tough to beat! I've been satisfied with every meal here, from brunches to casual date night dinners. The dry-aged burger is a personal favorite, and the ranche-quiles (breakfast nachos) have proved themselves a satisfying meal for tough post-party mornings. Usually less busy than other nearby restaurants, which makes it a low maintenance choice at popular times - don't wait 45 minutes for a table at brunch, go to District Kitchen!

Don't assume you will get Happy Hour prices if you come in during Happy Hour. You only get the price if you sit at the bar (assuming there is any space). We asked our waiter if we could order there and bring drinks to the table, and were told that was fine. When we attempted to do that, the bartender said that we would have to pay full price if we did that. Two of my party cancelled their order and left. I stayed for a somewhat mediocre (but not awful) beetroot and orange salad.
Good fries, good service, nice eggs Benedict with salmon special at brunch

I was excited to come here after reading such rave reviews. I even activated my OpenTable gift card to be used here because the happy hour menu looked incredible. My husband and I ordered a soft cow's milk cheese and blue cheese. The cheese was freezing cold, straight out of the fridge. I've never heard of anyone serving cheese cold like that. Every restaurant I've ordered cheese from has it clearly sitting out to be at delicious room temperature-- bringing out all the flavors of the cheese. And the cow's cheese was not a fresh cut-- it was hard on the side. The bartender gave me a dirty plate and she didn't check on us or ask how the food was for a solid 15 mins (the bar was NOT busy). This all should have been a sign but we kept going.  We ordered gnocchi and the sweet and spicy cauliflower. The gnocchi was not light and pillow-y and the "brown butter" sauce did not have the nutty, lovely taste of brown butter. It was quite gross but I was really hungry and ate most of it. The cauliflower on the other hand, we each had one bite and then didn't touch it. "Sweet and spicy" apparently meant limp cauliflower doused in soy sauce and hot sauce and covered in green onions.  The bartender only charged us for our drinks and gnocchi after we explained the situation, which I appreciated, but she never apologized. No manager or anyone from the kitchen came to check on the situation. One big disappointment. Not returning and trying to see if OpenTable will switch my giftcard to a different restaurant.
Great food!
Great desserts and great sized portions. No leftovers tonight.

Food was good. Service was poor. They forgot one of our orders and the waiter seem to be more interested in what was partaking across the street than at his own tables. Patio was very dirty and contained a lot of food on the ground. Dog friendly patio!!
Poor service. Actually left before anyone else came over to take my order.
Good food, good service.
Aside from the completely impersonal hostess... This was a good place for a late brunch.
Hipster spot. Bar was okay, but I don't see myself returning.

I'm mainly giving this rating because of how well they handled the conference crowd. They were busy and even though I didn't have a reservation they were able to seat me quickly. Someone came to take my order quickly and my food came out much faster than expected! Food was good. The gnocchi had a little too much going on for my taste because the parmesan was overwhelming but that and my salad were still good. I also noticed the servers were very patient with other tables. The table next to me wasn't ready the first 2 times he came to take their order but he simply said he would be right back and they didn't get annoyed.
Delicious food, great service, reasonable price if you can restrain yourself.
Great food and drink

Holy mediocre food. I'm not from DC, but at 20 dollars a dish i expected the food to either taste good or be huge. This was neither. Don't let the edgy hipster lights fool you, the place was a tourist trap.
Friendly staff and very good food at reasonable prices.  I loved the Seafood in Red Sauce!  And the NY strip on another night.
Far more intimate than I expected, with a far better menu. Chef's putting himself out there
Great place for dinner, amazing food and location.
Food was good. Staff was friendly. Super close to the National Zoo.
Great service, great location, incredible news takes on American and Spanish staple foods

Nice decor, very cozy. The servers are attentive and friendly. Very seafood heavy when looking at the menu. Overall great dine in experience and the price point is barely over fast casual dining ($16 burgers)
Great service great food

Had dinner here tonight and was very impressed. Sat outside on the patio and enjoyed the mild weather. I've sat at many patios before and typically service is lacking. Here however that was not the case.  We had a very attentive waiter who made some very nice recommendation. The who meal he was close but never hovered.  I had the steak and potatoes. Steak was cooked exactly the way I wanted it. I ordered medium well and there was just a hint of pink in the center. The wife had the paella and said it was almost as good as her grandmothers. The paella was in a prefix menu with an app we shared and a desert we shared.  When I'm in DC this is going to be on my rotation of places to eat.

Great prices for a traveler on food and drinks!!! Outside dinning or just sit at the bar. Waitstaff is excellent... Can be busy, but worth the wait... Your food will be too hot to eat when it comes to the table it's that fresh...

This place is Meh and so do. I only go back because my best friend likes it, but then I have to sit and listen to complaints about it that I heard last time. Eat here once and you've done all you can with it. The staff is underwhelming and the small menu that never changes is over priced.

A small and quaint place. The food was pretty good. my friend had their creekstone burger which he said was delicious. I had their 2606 omelete which wasnt as good as i had hoped. they did a poor job with the mushrooms and the cheese in it. it just felt haphazardly thrown together.

Absolutely awesome experience! I'd popped in before and vowed to return. Glad I did. Halibut is in season & the fresh preparation was complimentary. Also had the foie gras - silky. Must have the jalapeño cocktail.  Sevice at bar was exceptional.
Really excellent food and drinks. Great service too. They offer half portions of many entrees, which is awesome if for getting a high quality meal for pretty cheap.

Only eaten here a few times and the food's been decent, but they have excellent happy hour specials which makes it a great destination if you're looking to unwind after work or meet up with someone for a quick drink.
Get the PBLT sandwich for brunch, that was one of the best ciabatta sandwich I've ever had.  Truly incredible!
Great food, and fantastic service!

Shockingly Expensive - We came by Saturday night after Zoo Lights as a party of 6 at around 9:30 PM. We were seated quickly, but the time between the order taking and the food delivery was long. Service was good otherwise as was the food, but the prices were the highest you're likely to see. An Irish Coffee, 2 cheese burgers with fries and a beer cost $68 dollars after all was said and done. Even the bacon bits added $2 to her burger after the $2 for the slice of cheese. Tax was 10 percent and gratuity was 18 percent for a party of 6. The menu up front that got us to enter had happy hour prices that we'd never see. Less the drinks, McDonalds was 2 doors down and offered the same basic fare we had at a fifth what we paid. None of us could figure out light fare came to $184 for six people.  We spent 20 minutes debating the bill and reprocessing in disbelief. What is $68 for 2 burgers and a couple drinks in DC anyway?  As I said to my girl; it would have been a spending spree for her at the shoe store. Nice place, but if you come, plan to spend big. We later found out that due to an error, we were undercharged by a dollar.

Great food, good drinks, not that expensive. Fresh and wonderfully prepared scallops. Jalapeño polenta is perfect consistency & flavor. Mussels were perfectly cooked and served in a tasty tomato sauce. Tuna tartare was wonderful - like sushi on toast - great sesame flavor without overwhelming the tuna.  Drinks were decent: good cocktails, pretty good beer & wine selection. They do serve a good number of local brews, so big bonus points for that.  Will try to get back after the next zoo visit!
Ate here twice and enjoyed the burgers calamari and deserts.
French fries here are AMAZING. Crispy on the outside and soft on the inside. Shrimp + polenta dish was also phenomenal and beautifully placed. Service was a bit slow but the food was delicious!
Not the biggest of menus, but it doesn't matter as the food is beautifully cooked. Also a great choice of drinks, decent prices and friendly service. Definitely worth a visit.
Only had a few drinks but this was one of the few places in the area that had some local brews on tap/bottle/can (as opposed to Miller Lite/Heineken/etc). Fine service, tasty beers.  Good desert

We loved this restaurant in Woodley Park. It seems relatively new. The menu was not extensive, but the food was quite good. They also offer half plates of pasta which is nice to allow sampling of various items. The indoor space is warm and inviting. They also have a nice outdoor space on Connecticut for people watching. The service was friendly though a bit slow. The beer selection was limited with just a few drafts but they do have a few good beers. They were kid friendly with high chairs. We'll be back.
